<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/kha_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/kha_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Lansdale, PA: 3 Feb 02<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.94)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=498'>Doug "Phrim" Faust</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=498&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 7, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Tournament Report - Sun 3 Feb 02<br>
NeoQuest Games in Lansdale, PA<br>
<br>
Another month, another tournament at NeoQuest...  Except this time, Kim Caton, the director, had something special planned: she was giving an entire box of boosters away to the first prize winner!  Anyway, after a lousy showing a couple weeks ago at Woodbridge (2-2), I&#39;ve been gradually tweaking my deck so that it&#39;s really hard to overwhelm Frodo.  In the 15 tournament games that I&#39;ve played before this, all 4 of my losses have been because I was overwhelmed, I&#39;ve yet to lose the race.  So I put in Thrarin, and a couple Thror&#39;s Maps to find my rivers and forests for ARV and to make sure I never, ever see that wretched no-archery site.  The Shadow side required a bit more thought though.  I liked the Sauron half I had built, but the big problem was against Tennet-style pool-choke decks that Mike Dalton and possibly other good players might be playing, those Sauron cards got stuck in your hand like nothing else.  So I decided to go with Moria, which typically can do the best with little pool to work with, and can also do a decent job at slowing the opponent down.<br>
<br>
So I get up on the morning of the tournament and take a shower.  And we all know that all the best ideas come from thinking in the shower. :-)  So I&#39;m there thinking about what I should bid, 1 or 2 was all that I really should bid against Nazgul, who want to go second anyway, but I could really get in trouble if I didn&#39;t know what the opponent was playing and ended up going second.  The way I&#39;m playing, I can&#39;t afford to go second.  So I decide to hell with the Prancing Pony, and instead bid 5 and start Green Dragon for a Sam that will remove 3 burdens and then die and stop cluttering up my fellowship.  I compensate for the lack of Pony by using 4 Aragorns (took out Boromir who only got in the way anyway), so I&#39;m sure to get him quickly, and he always needs to be healed anyway.  I hadn&#39;t seen anyone else in the area bidding anywhere near that, so I thought with it I&#39;d be able to go first every time.  So after a few modifications to my sites, I felt I had a deck that could win a tournament.<br>
<br>
So I drive up to NeoQuest in Lansdale, and get there around 15 minutes early expecting to get some trades or a quick game in.  Judging by last month&#39;s attendance of 11, I wasn&#39;t expecting many people to be there, especially with it being Superbowl Sunday.  I walk in, and the place is a madhouse.  In the end, we had 23 people for the tournament, including some of the best in New Jersey and Pennsylvania.  Among them were Mike Dalton, John Lolli, Bob Caton, Scott Landis, Andy Parks, as well as a crew from central PA courtesy of Jim Van Fleet.  So the tournament was probably the biggest and most competitive tournament yet in the area.<br>
<br>
Game 1: Me vs. Ted Panczyszyn&#39;s (1500) Ranger/Nazgul deck<br>
<br>
Ted is a seasoned Star Wars CCG veteran, but this is only his second LOTR tournament.  He went 0-4 in the last tournament using Bob&#39;s wacky Dwarf deck, but this week he was using Kim&#39;s tournament-winning Nazgul deck, since Kim opted not to play.  So I quite easily go first, and start moving right along.  He&#39;s making some strange plays because he&#39;s pretty new, like playing All Blades Perish at odd times, but he does manage to kill one of my fellowship (besides Sam).  On the other hand, my Trolls and things are just ripping his fellowship to pieces, and I manage to kill everyone except Aragorn and Frodo.  So at site 6 I play 4 guys, so I have 2 guys to assign myself.  Of course, instead of being a chump and putting them both on Frodo, I put an extra on each so I&#39;m overwhelming BOTH Aragorn and Frodo.  He of course plays PATHS to save Frodo, but he has nothing to save Aragorn.  So as it stands he&#39;s at site 6, and I&#39;m at site 7, and it&#39;s my turn.  I move to 8, and he plays two big Nazgul who I don&#39;t kill right away because I can&#39;t find an ARV.  I could move to 9 because I think I have enough directed archery to knock one of them out, but since he&#39;s in no danger of winning and there&#39;s enough time left, I sit tight and let him move.  He doesn&#39;t have any extra companions, so he moves to 7 where he finds 3 big Orcs and gets overwhelmed.  Full Win, Total: 3pts<br>
<br>
Highlights: Killing Aragorn because I anticipated PATHS.<br>
Lowlights: Blade Tips are annoying<br>
<br>
Game 2: Me vs. Bob Caton&#39;s (1607) Nazgul deck<br>
<br>
To be honest, I can&#39;t remember what Bob was playing for Fellowship because it didn&#39;t really come into play that much.  I went first and stayed ahead the entire game.  I played ARV at site 3, and he couldn&#39;t really stop me at the middle sites, and Bob was getting some bad draws and pretty much couldn&#39;t do anything to me.  Of course, I pretty much didn&#39;t touch his fellowship either, but since I was ahead that didn&#39;t matter.  Basically I got all the right draws, Bob got all the wrong draws, so I won in 4 moves.  Full Win, Total: 6pts<br>
<br>
Highlights: Well I did get all the right draws :-)<br>
Lowlights: Can&#39;t really remember too much of this game, unfortunately<br>
<br>
Game 3: Me vs. Scott Landis&#39;s (1553) Gandalf/Nazgul-Sauron Combo<br>
<br>
Despite this only being Scott&#39;s second tournament, he&#39;s a very good player, and tied with me for second at last month&#39;s tournament.  I go first obviously, but he stops me with two of those big beefy Sauron minions that make you discard.  So he goes, and I don&#39;t do much to him, and then my turn comes around again.  I started with a bunch of man possessions in my hand, and I finally just drew Aragorn.  Problem was, I had already played Gandalf, and Sam was still alive, so playing him would give me 6 companions.  I decide to do it anyway, since Sauron decks don&#39;t have much to combat 6 companions, so I play Aragorn, his Bow, and some other stuff like Gwemegil, and then of course I find out he&#39;s playing Nazgul too and drops Enquea on me.  So Enquea knocks out Arwen with her newly-acquired sword, and then I of course kill Enquea with an arrow.  Since he&#39;s playing Sauron, I clear off the rest of my burdens after Sam heals at the sanctuary (and then Sam spectacularly dies, as he ought to), so his Enduring Evils don&#39;t do much.  I&#39;m really not sure what exactly he was trying to do with his deck, he was playing a lot of the Sauron discard minions, and he played Thin and Stretched on me, but I didn&#39;t see any Desperate Defense or anything else to make me discard or add burdens.  *shrug*  Anyway, I manage to get back ahead of him at the middle sites, and then my ARVs started kicking in, so the end sites weren&#39;t too much of a problem.  He makes it to site 8, so I push from 7 to 9, and I&#39;m ready with the ARV at his Tol Brandir, but he doesn&#39;t have enough and just concedes anyway.  Full Win, Total: 9pts<br>
<br>
Highlights: Staying ahead to win the race...<br>
Lowlights: Why does Enquea always show up the turn you put down the 6th companion?  Sheesh!<br>
<br>
Game 4: Me vs. John Lolli&#39;s (1609) Cardflow deck with Moria<br>
<br>
John was playing a strange 80-card deck starting Sam with uncommon Gimli, of all people.  Not sure exactly what the Gimli was for, he never used him.  Anyway, he was using lots and lots of card drawing gimmicks like Elrond and Delving.  We start off right away with a problem: we both bid 5!  So we both roll a 20-sided die, I get a 13, and he gets a 14, so he goes first, and I&#39;m in trouble.  I don&#39;t at all have the hand to stop him from getting to site 3, so he goes right to the sanctuary, and it&#39;s my turn.  I play a bunch of stuff, including Sam and Gandalf and some possessions, so he has a bunch of pool when I move to site 2.  Enough to play a Keyward and a Troll with his Hammer!  Certainly not something you expect to see at site 2.  But there&#39;s a reason I&#39;m playing with the Breeland *FOREST*, so I play ARV, kill the Troll with an arrow and have Gandalf finish off the Keyward.  So the end result is that I&#39;m not really wounded when I get to site 3, which happens to be my Rivendell Waterfall, so I move on to site 4.  So on his turn, he moves to site 4, and I play a bunch of stuff, but he kills everything except a Keyward.  And then he stops.  He stops!!!  This was the best possible thing that could happen for me, he could&#39;ve just moved straight on to site 6 because of my Waterfall (and with my crappy hand it was certainly possible), but he decided to stop, putting me in the lead.  In the meanwhile, I start finding my Trolls and killing off some of his many companions, and I certainly don&#39;t let him get back ahead of me at any cost.  I think he moved to my site 8, expecting it to be Shores of Nan Hithoel like you see in many Moria decks, but I don&#39;t play cards that get my fellowship in traps, and it&#39;s just Pillars of the Kings.  So I&#39;m able to make the 7 to 9 move, and I use Thror&#39;s Map to make site 9 Tol Brandir so I can use my ARV.  But he doesn&#39;t have that much for me and I win.  Full Win, Total: 12pts<br>
<br>
Highlights: Winning the race after going 2nd!<br>
Lowlights: He probably should have kept moving, and then I would&#39;ve lost...<br>
<br>
Game 5: Me vs. Andrew Parks&#39;s (1551) Arrows, Allies, and Nazgul<br>
<br>
Andy had previously beaten heavy-hitter Mike Dalton in a real close game, giving Mike his only loss of the night, and then had taken down Bill Kafer, so myself and Andy were the only undefeateds at this point.  However, he had a timed win.  So the way it worked is this: if I won in any fashion, I would win the tournament; if Andy got a full win, he would win the tournament; and if Andy got a timed win, there would be something on the order of 4-5 people with 13 points.  Anyway, Andy and I have played each other plenty of times casually, so I knew what his deck was, but he hadn&#39;t seen this particular incarnation of my deck yet (especially since I thought up part of it in the shower this morning).  Anyway, I go first, and luckily I get an opening hand Thror&#39;s Map, which is real nice against Nazgul.  So I map the first two sites to make his Nazgul nice and expensive, but I&#39;m too wounded to move to site 4 from my Waterfall.  He does likewise, and stops at site 3.  So I move on to site 4, and I find 3 fierce Nazgul, and I&#39;m bigger than none of them.  Ugh.  So if I don&#39;t move on, he could get ahead of me, but there&#39;s no way I can move against 3 fierce Nazgul if I can&#39;t kill any of them.  So I reluctantly stop.  I draw nothing spectacular on the minion side, making me doubtful about being able to stop him.  And to complicate things, he has Galadriel Mirroring me to death.  So I&#39;m left with like 3 minions and a Scimitar.  So I play them, and with the Scimitar, I draw... (dramatic pause) ...the Cave Troll!  So I happily add the Troll to the mix, and force him to stop.  Then I draw up an insane minion hand, including another Troll, the Keyward, and the Hammer.  So I move to site 5, and he plays a bunch of Nazgul on me, and now I&#39;m really wounded.  I could go to site 6 if I really wanted to, since it would be Lothlorien Woods and I have an ARV, but I decide that I can hold off for now and definitely stop him, knowing what I have for minions.  So on his turn, he opts not to Mirror me so he can play Elrond for free with Galadriel and hopefully draw Celeborn to Mirror me twice anyway, but he doesn&#39;t get Celeborn, so he moves on and I drop lots on him.  I end up killing a bunch of his companions, and he has to decide whether to feed Arwen or Legolas to the Troll, and goes with Arwen.  Which leaves him with only Legolas and Frodo, which might be a problem when he gets to Silverlode Banks.  I&#39;ve drawn up a bunch of stuff to heal my guys, so with the help of ARV I plow through to site 7.  He&#39;s fortunately finally drawn his one Aragorn, and I can&#39;t touch him at site 6 because of the swarm of allies (especially archer allies).  But he&#39;s running short on Nazgul because he played so many of them at the middle sites, so I run to site 9, using Thror&#39;s Map to switch site 9 to Tol Brandir so he didn&#39;t get to draw extra cards for my burdens, and win the game.  Full Win, Total: 15pts<br>
<br>
Highlights: Pulling the Cave Troll with a Scimitar when I REALLY needed it!<br>
Lowlights: Usually don&#39;t have that much trouble against Nazgul...<br>
<br>
So anyway, I won the tournament and got the booster box.  It was a decent box, with the notables being Gimli, Boromir, and Lurtz.  Also had a lot of the cards I was missing, so that&#39;s good.  Scott Landis took second place and got a $25 gift certificate, with 3rd going to Mike Dalton and 4th going to Andy Parks, all of whom had one loss apiece.  Obviously it was a good tournament for me, and I was really glad to see so many people show up.<br>
<br>
Until next time...<br>
<br>
--<br>
Doug Faust<br>
